	shorttitle = {Social dominance orientation},
	abstract = {Social dominance orientation ({SDO}), one's degree of preference for inequality among social groups, is introduced. On the basis of social dominance theory, it is shown that (1) men are more social dominance-oriented than women, (2) high-{SDO} people seek hierarchy-enhancing professional roles and low-{SDO} people seek hierarchy-attenuating roles, (3) {SDO} was related to beliefs in a large number of social and political ideologies that support group-based hierarchy (e.g., meritocracy and racism) and to support for policies that have implications for intergroup relations (e.g., war, civil rights, and social programs), including new policies. {SDO} was distinguished from interpersonal dominance, conservatism, and authoritarianism. {SDO} was negatively correlated with empathy, tolerance, communality, and altruism. The ramifications of {SDO} in social context are discussed. ({PsycInfo} Database Record (c) 2020 {APA}, all rights reserved)},
